comments.body:
@abadger in this case we know for sure that v0.6.0 will add extra arguments w/o defaults to some hooks 100% breaking the API so before changing the upper bound, we'll have to adjust that. Besides, we now have a designated location in the tree where the packagers can drop-in libs w/o having to package them separately if they wish so.

But I see your point: deb packages infamous for regularly breaking pip and other Python packaging-related things. Ref: https://gist.github.com/tiran/2dec9e03c6f901814f6d1e8dad09528e.

Anyway... We have to specify what exactly is supported right now, this info gets into the metadata and the packagers are responsible for not breaking stuff. If we say that 0.6.0 is not supported and they ignore the instruction, it's not our fault, is it?
